{
  "id": "ellis_bronnikov",
  "name": "Ellis-Bronnikov",
  "description": "A static, spherically symmetric traversable wormhole with zero redshift function, also known as the drainhole metric.",
  "tags": [
    "wormhole",
    "exotic matter",
    "traversable",
    "static",
    "spherically symmetric",
    "stationary"
  ],
  "signature": "(-,+,+,+)",
  "convention": "The time coordinate is $ct$. The coordinate $r$ is the proper radial distance, $r \\in (-\\infty,\\infty)$, with the wormhole throat at $r = 0$. The parameter $\\ell > 0$ is the throat radius.",
  "history": "1973 produced, in two independent papers, one of the earliest known examples of a geodesically complete wormhole geometry in general relativity. Homer Ellis, working at the University of Colorado, wrote down what he called a \"drainhole\" — a solution to the Einstein equations coupled to a massless phantom scalar field, characterized by a throat connecting two asymptotically flat regions [ellis1973]. Kirill Bronnikov, working independently in the Soviet Union, found the same solution the same year by a different route [bronnikov1973]. Neither author was thinking primarily about traversability; that framing would come fifteen years later.¶What Ellis and Bronnikov had found was remarkable on its own terms. The metric is geodesically complete — there is no singularity anywhere, and the two asymptotically flat ends are connected by a smooth throat of radius $\\ell$. The price is a phantom scalar field, a matter source with the wrong-sign kinetic term that violates the null energy condition. This was the first clear instance of what Morris and Thorne would later identify as the exotic matter requirement [morris1988]: the wormhole geometry is geometrically clean but physically costly.¶The solution sat quietly in the literature until the late 1980s, when the traversable wormhole program brought it renewed attention [visser1995]. It is now a standard example in graduate GR — simple enough to work with by hand, rich enough to illustrate the essential tension between wormhole geometry and energy conditions.",
  "references": [
    "ellis1973",
    "bronnikov1973",
    "morris1988",
    "visser1995"
  ],
